"Gargano D., Vecchio G., Bernardo L.","Plant-soil relationships in fragments of Mediterranean snow-beds: Ecological and conservation implications",2010,"Plant Ecology","207","1",,"175","189",,,10.1007/s11258-009-9663-7,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-75949125355&partnerID=40&md5=c4c178d95782a4bbea37f6fe11780f43","Dipartimento di Ecologia dell'Università della Calabria, 87036 Arcavacata di Rende, Italy; Museo di Storia Naturale della Calabria ed Orto Botanico dell'Università della Calabria, 87036 Arcavacata di Rende, Italy; TechfemSud, S.S. 280 Bivio Aeroporto n. 2, 88046 Lamezia Terme, Italy","Gargano, D., Dipartimento di Ecologia dell'Università della Calabria, 87036 Arcavacata di Rende, Italy, Museo di Storia Naturale della Calabria ed Orto Botanico dell'Università della Calabria, 87036 Arcavacata di Rende, Italy; Vecchio, G., TechfemSud, S.S. 280 Bivio Aeroporto n. 2, 88046 Lamezia Terme, Italy; Bernardo, L., Dipartimento di Ecologia dell'Università della Calabria, 87036 Arcavacata di Rende, Italy, Museo di Storia Naturale della Calabria ed Orto Botanico dell'Università della Calabria, 87036 Arcavacata di Rende, Italy","We investigated the spatial structures of soil properties and snow-bed vegetation, and their relationships, in southern Italy. We analyzed data on 26 plant species and 10 soil traits from adjacent 1 × 1 m plots in two snow-bed patches. Measures of spatial autocorrelation revealed striking spatial structures for plant cover and soil properties at both sites. Bivariate statistics and Mantel tests highlighted a significant correlation between spatial patterns of plants and soil in the study sites. Canonical correspondence analysis related such relationships to an ecological gradient connecting soil properties and plant assemblages in this unusual ecological context. Among the variables significantly related to plant patterns is the soil organic matter, which is recognized as being sensitive to global warming. Our analyses suggest that soil dynamics due to increasing temperature may promote the replacement of species typical of southern snow-bed ecosystems by more mesophilous plants. © Springer Science+Business Media B.V. 2009.","Canonical correspondence analysis; Ecological gradients; Global warming; Snow-bed vegetation; South Italy; Spatial structure","canonical analysis; conservation planning; ecological zonation; global warming; soil dynamics; soil organic matter; soil temperature; spatial analysis; Italy",,,,,,"Abbate, G., Avena, G.C., Blasi, C., Pastures with Bromus erectus Hudson at the Mula, Muletta and Cozzo Pellegrino Mountains (western Calabria, southern Italy) (1984) Ann Bot (Rome), 42, pp. 67-74; Aerts, R., The freezer defrosting: Global warming and litter decomposition rates in cold biomes (2006) J Ecol, 94, pp. 713-724; Barnard, R., Le Roux, X., Hungate, B.A., Several components of global change alter nitrifying and denitrifying activities in an annual grassland (2006) Funct Ecol, 20, pp. 557-564; Beatty, S.W., Influence of microtopography and canopy species on spatial patterns of forest understory plants (1984) Ecology, 65, pp. 1406-1419; Biondi, E., Ballelli, S., Allegrezza, M., La vegetazione dell'ordine Brometalia erecti Br.-Bl. 1936 nell'Appennino (Italia) (1995) Fitosociologia, 30, pp. 3-45; Bonin, G., Première contribution a l'étude des pelouses mésophiles et des groupements hygrophiles du Monte Pollino (1972) Phyton (Horn), 14 (3-4), pp. 271-280; Cairns, D.M., A comparison of methods for predicting vegetation type (2001) Plant Ecol, 156, pp. 3-18; Calef, M.P., McGuire, A.D., Epstein, H.E., Analysis of vegetation distribution in Interior Alaska and sensitivity to climate change using a logistic regression approach (2005) J Biogeogr, 32, pp. 863-878; Choler, P., Michalet, R., Callaway, R.M., Facilitation and competition on gradients in alpine plant communities (2001) Ecology, 82, pp. 3295-3308; Conti, F., Abbate, G., Alessandrini, A., (2005) An Annotated Checklist of the 